# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apicomplexan
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The **Apicomplexa** (also called **Apicomplexia**; single: **apicomplexan**) are organisms of a large phylum of mainly parasitic alveolates.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Most possess a unique form of organelle structure that comprises a type of non-photosynthetic plastid called an apicoplast—with an apical complex membrane.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The organelle's apical shape is an adaptation that the apicomplexan applies in penetrating a host cell.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The Apicomplexa are unicellular and spore-forming.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Most are obligate endoparasites of animals, except *Nephromyces*, a symbiont in marine animals, originally classified as a chytrid fungus.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Motile structures such as flagella or pseudopods are present only in certain gamete stages.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The Apicomplexa are a diverse group that includes organisms such as the coccidia, gregarines, piroplasms, haemogregarines, and plasmodia.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The name Apicomplexa derives from two Latin words—*apex* (top) and *complexus* (infolds)—for the set of organelles in the sporozoite.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The Apicomplexa comprise the bulk of what used to be called the **Sporozoa**, a group of parasitic protozoans, in general without flagella, cilia, or pseudopods.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Most of the Apicomplexa can use gliding motility, that uses adhesions and small static myosin motors.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The other main lines of this obsolete grouping were the Ascetosporea (a group of Rhizaria), the Myxozoa (highly derived cnidarian animals), and the Microsporidia (derived from fungi).
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Sometimes, the name Sporozoa is taken as a synonym for the Apicomplexa, or occasionally as a subset.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The phylum Apicomplexa contains all eukaryotes with a group of structures and organelles collectively termed the apical complex.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] This complex consists of structural components and secretory organelles required for invasion of host cells during the parasitic stages of the Apicomplexan life cycle.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Apicomplexa have complex life cycles, involving several stages and typically undergoing both asexual and sexual replication.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] All Apicomplexa are obligate parasites for some portion of their life cycle, with some parasitizing two separate hosts for their asexual and sexual stages.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Besides the conserved apical complex, Apicomplexa are morphologically diverse.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Different organisms within Apicomplexa, as well as different life stages for a given apicomplexan, can vary substantially in size, shape, and subcellular structure.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Like other eukaryotes, Apicomplexa have a nucleus, endoplasmic reticulum and Golgi complex.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Apicomplexa generally have a single mitochondrion, as well as another endosymbiont-derived organelle called the apicoplast which maintains a separate 35 kilobase circular genome (with the exception of *Cryptosporidium* species and *Gregarina niphandrodes* which lack an apicoplast).
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] All members of this phylum have an infectious stage—the sporozoite—which possesses three distinct structures in an apical complex.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The apical complex consists of a set of spirally arranged microtubules (the conoid), a secretory body (the rhoptry) and one or more polar rings.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Additional slender electron-dense secretory bodies (micronemes) surrounded by one or two polar rings may also be present.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] This structure gives the phylum its name.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] A further group of spherical organelles is distributed throughout the cell rather than being localized at the apical complex and are known as the dense granules.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] These typically have a mean diameter around 0.7 μm.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Secretion of the dense-granule content takes place after parasite invasion and localization within the parasitophorous vacuole and persists for several minutes.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Apicomplexans have a unique gliding capability which enables them to cross through tissues and enter and leave their host cells.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] This gliding ability is made possible by the use of adhesions and small static myosin motors.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Other features common to this phylum are a lack of cilia, sexual reproduction, use of micropores for feeding, and the production of oocysts containing sporozoites as the infective form.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Transposons appear to be rare in this phylum, but have been identified in the genera *Ascogregarina* and *Eimeria*.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Most members have a complex lifecycle, involving both asexual and sexual reproduction.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Typically, a host is infected via an active invasion by the parasites (similar to entosis), which divide to produce sporozoites that enter its cells.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Eventually, the cells burst, releasing merozoites, which infect new cells.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] This may occur several times, until gamonts are produced, forming gametes that fuse to create new cysts.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Many variations occur on this basic pattern, however, and many Apicomplexa have more than one host.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The apical complex includes vesicles called rhoptries and micronemes, which open at the anterior of the cell.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] These secrete enzymes that allow the parasite to enter other cells.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The tip is surrounded by a band of microtubules, called the polar ring, and among the Conoidasida is also a funnel of tubulin proteins called the conoid.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Over the rest of the cell, except for a diminished mouth called the micropore, the membrane is supported by vesicles called alveoli, forming a semirigid pellicle.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The presence of alveoli and other traits place the Apicomplexa among a group called the alveolates.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Several related flagellates, such as *Perkinsus* and *Colpodella*, have structures similar to the polar ring and were formerly included here, but most appear to be closer relatives of the dinoflagellates.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] They are probably similar to the common ancestor of the two groups.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Another similarity is that many apicomplexan cells contain a single plastid, called the apicoplast, surrounded by either three or four membranes.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Its functions are thought to include tasks such as lipid and heme biosynthesis, and it appears to be necessary for survival.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] In general, plastids are considered to have a common origin with the chloroplasts of dinoflagellates, and evidence points to an origin from red algae rather than green.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Within this phylum are four groups — coccidians, gregarines, haemosporidians (or haematozoans, including in addition piroplasms), and marosporidians.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The coccidians and haematozoans appear to be relatively closely related.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The gregarines are generally parasites of annelids, arthropods, and molluscs.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] They are often found in the guts of their hosts, but may invade the other tissues.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] In the typical gregarine lifecycle, a trophozoite develops within a host cell into a schizont.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] This then divides into a number of merozoites by schizogony.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The merozoites are released by lysing the host cell, which in turn invade other cells.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] At some point in the apicomplexan lifecycle, gametocytes are formed.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] These are released by lysis of the host cells, which group together.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The gametes fuse with another to form oocysts.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The oocysts leave the host to be taken up by a new host.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] In general, coccidians are parasites of vertebrates.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Like gregarines, they are commonly parasites of the epithelial cells of the gut, but may infect other tissues.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The coccidian lifecycle involves merogony, gametogony, and sporogony.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] While similar to that of the gregarines it differs in zygote formation.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Some trophozoites enlarge and become macrogamete, whereas others divide repeatedly to form microgametes (anisogamy).
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The microgametes are motile and must reach the macrogamete to fertilize it.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The fertilized macrogamete forms a zygote that in its turn forms an oocyst that is normally released from the body.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Syzygy, when it occurs, involves markedly anisogamous gametes.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The lifecycle is typically haploid, with the only diploid stage occurring in the zygote, which is normally short-lived.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The main difference between the coccidians and the gregarines is in the gamonts.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] In the coccidia, these are small, intracellular, and without epimerites or mucrons.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] In the gregarines, these are large, extracellular, and possess epimerites or mucrons.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] A second difference between the coccidia and the gregarines also lies in the gamonts.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] In the coccidians, a single gamont becomes a macrogametocyte, whereas in the gregarines, the gamonts give rise to multiple gametocytes.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The Haemosporidia have more complex lifecycles that alternate between an arthropod and a vertebrate host.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The trophozoite parasitises erythrocytes or other tissues in the vertebrate host.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Microgametes and macrogametes are always found in the blood.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The gametes are taken up by the insect vector during a blood meal.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The microgametes migrate within the gut of the insect vector and fuse with the macrogametes.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The fertilized macrogamete now becomes an ookinete, which penetrates the body of the vector.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The ookinete then transforms into an oocyst and divides initially by meiosis and then by mitosis (haplontic lifecycle) to give rise to the sporozoites.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The sporozoites escape from the oocyst and migrate within the body of the vector to the salivary glands where they are injected into the new vertebrate host when the insect vector feeds again.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The class Marosporida Mathur, Kristmundsson, Gestal, Freeman, and Keeling 2020 is a newly recognized lineage of apicomplexans that is sister to the Coccidia and Hematozoa.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] It is defined as a phylogenetic clade containing *Aggregata octopiana* Frenzel 1885, *Merocystis kathae* Dakin, 1911 (both Aggregatidae, originally coccidians), *Rhytidocystis* sp.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] 2019 (Rhytidocystidae Levine, 1979, originally coccidians, Agamococcidiorida), and *Margolisiella islandica* Kristmundsson et al.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] 2011 (closely related to Rhytidocystidae).
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Marosporida infect marine invertebrates.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Members of this clade retain plastid genomes and the canonical apicomplexan plastid metabolism.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] However, marosporidians have the most reduced apicoplast genomes sequenced to date, lack canonical plastidial RNA polymerase and so provide new insights into reductive organelle evolution.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Many of the apicomplexan parasites are important pathogens of humans and domestic animals.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] In contrast to bacterial pathogens, these apicomplexan parasites are eukaryotic and share many metabolic pathways with their animal hosts.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] This makes therapeutic target development extremely difficult – a drug that harms an apicomplexan parasite is also likely to harm its human host.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] At present, no effective vaccines are available for most diseases caused by these parasites.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Biomedical research on these parasites is challenging because it is often difficult, if not impossible, to maintain live parasite cultures in the laboratory and to genetically manipulate these organisms.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] In recent years, several of the apicomplexan species have been selected for genome sequencing.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The availability of genome sequences provides a new opportunity for scientists to learn more about the evolution and biochemical capacity of these parasites.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The predominant source of this genomic information is the EuPathDB family of websites, which currently provides specialised services for *Plasmodium* species (PlasmoDB), coccidians (ToxoDB), piroplasms (PiroplasmaDB), and *Cryptosporidium* species (CryptoDB).
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] One possible target for drugs is the plastid, and in fact existing drugs such as tetracyclines, which are effective against apicomplexans, seem to operate against the plastid.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Many Coccidiomorpha have an intermediate host, as well as a definitive host, and the evolution of hosts proceeded in different ways and at different times in these groups.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] For most coccidiomorphs, the original host has remained the definitive host and the newly acquired host(s) acted as intermediate hosts.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Similar strategies to increase the likelihood of transmission have evolved in multiple genera.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Polyenergid oocysts and tissue cysts are found in representatives of the orders Protococcidiorida and Eimeriida.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Hypnozoites are found in *Karyolysus lacerate* and most species of *Plasmodium*; transovarial transmission of parasites occurs in lifecycles of *Karyolysus* and *Babesia*.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Horizontal gene transfer appears to have occurred early on in this phylum's evolution with the transfer of a histone H4 lysine 20 (H4K20) modifier, KMT5A (Set8), from an animal host to the ancestor of apicomplexans.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] A second gene—H3K36 methyltransferase (Ashr3 in plants)—may have also been horizontally transferred.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Within the Adelorina are species that infect invertebrates and others that infect vertebrates.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The Eimeriorina—the largest suborder in this phylum—the lifecycle involves both sexual and asexual stages.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The asexual stages reproduce by schizogony.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The male gametocyte produces a large number of gametes and the zygote gives rise to an oocyst, which is the infective stage.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The majority are monoxenous (infect one host only), but a few are heteroxenous (lifecycle involves two or more hosts).
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The number of families in this later suborder is debated, with the number of families being between one and 20 depending on the authority and the number of genera being between 19 and 25.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The first Apicomplexa protozoan was seen by Antonie van Leeuwenhoek, who in 1674 saw probably oocysts of *Eimeria stiedae* in the gall bladder of a rabbit.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The first species of the phylum to be described, *Gregarina ovata*, in earwigs' intestines, was named by Dufour in 1828.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] He thought that they were a peculiar group related to the trematodes, at that time included in Vermes.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Since then, many more have been identified and named.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] During 1826–1850, 41 species and six genera of Apicomplexa were named.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The older taxon Sporozoa, included in Protozoa, was created by Leuckart in 1879 and adopted by Bütschli in 1880.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Through history, it grouped with the current Apicomplexa many unrelated groups.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] For example, Kudo (1954) included in the Sporozoa species of the Ascetosporea (Rhizaria), Microsporidia (Fungi), Myxozoa (Animalia), and *Helicosporidium* (Chlorophyta), while Zierdt (1978) included the genus *Blastocystis* (Stramenopiles).
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] *Dermocystidium* was also thought to be sporozoan.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Not all of these groups had spores, but all were parasitic.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] If they had cell walls, they also could be included in plant kingdom between bacteria or yeasts.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Sporozoa is no longer regarded as biologically valid and its use is discouraged, although some authors still use it as a synonym for the Apicomplexa.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] More recently, other groups were excluded from Apicomplexa, e.g., *Perkinsus* and *Colpodella* (now in Protalveolata).
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The field of classifying Apicomplexa is in flux and classification has changed throughout the years since it was formally named in 1970.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] By 1987, a comprehensive survey of the phylum was completed: in all, 4516 species and 339 genera had been named.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Although considerable revision of this phylum has been done (the order Haemosporidia now has 17 genera rather than 9), these numbers are probably still approximately correct.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Jacques Euzéby in 1988 created a new class Haemosporidiasina by merging subclass Piroplasmasina and suborder Haemospororina.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The division into Achromatorida and Chromatorida, although proposed on morphological grounds, may have a biological basis, as the ability to store haemozoin appears to have evolved only once.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The adeleorins are one-host parasites of invertebrates or vertebrates, or two-host parasites that alternately infect haematophagous (blood-feeding) invertebrates and the blood of vertebrates.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The eimeriorins are a diverse group that includes one host species of invertebrates, two-host species of invertebrates, one-host species of vertebrates and two-host species of vertebrates.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The eimeriorins are frequently called the coccidia.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] This term is often used to include the adeleorins.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Haemospororins, often known as the malaria parasites, are two-host Apicomplexa that parasitize blood-feeding dipteran flies and the blood of various tetrapod vertebrates.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Piroplasms where all the species included are two-host parasites infecting ticks and vertebrates.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Perkins et al. proposed the following scheme.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Macrogamete and microgamete develop separately.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Heteroxenous: alternates between vertebrate host (in which merogony occurs) and invertebrate host (in which sporogony occurs).
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Usually blood parasites, transmitted by blood-sucking insects.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The name Protospiromonadida has been proposed for the common ancestor of the Gregarinomorpha and Coccidiomorpha.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Another group of organisms that belong in this taxon are the corallicolids.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] These are found in coral reef gastric cavities.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Their relationship to the others in this phylum has yet to be established.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Another genus has been identified - *Nephromyces* - which appears to be a sister taxon to the Hematozoa.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] This genus is found in the renal sac of molgulid ascidian tunicates.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Members of this phylum, except for the photosynthetic chromerids, are parasitic and evolved from a free-living ancestor.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] This lifestyle is presumed to have evolved at the time of the divergence of dinoflagellates and apicomplexans.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Further evolution of this phylum has been estimated to have occurred about 800 million years ago.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The oldest extant clade is thought to be the archigregarines.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] These phylogenetic relations have rarely been studied at the subclass level.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The Haemosporidia are related to the gregarines, and the piroplasms and coccidians are sister groups.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] The Haemosporidia and the Piroplasma appear to be sister clades, and are more closely related to the coccidians than to the gregarines.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] Marosporida is a sister group to Coccidiomorphea.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] 2015 presents a somewhat different phylogeny, supporting the work of others showing multiple events of plastids losing photosynthesis.
[src:apicomplexan/apicomplexa] More importantly this work provides the first phylogenetic evidence that there have also been multiple events of plastids becoming genome-free.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] As the study of biology became increasingly specialized, specific codes were adopted for different types of organism.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] To an end-user who only deals with names of species, with some awareness that species are assignable to genera, families, and other taxa of higher ranks, it may not be noticeable that there is more than one code, but beyond this basic level these are rather different in the way they work.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] Such a name is called a **binomial name** (which may be shortened to just "binomial"), a **binomen**, **binominal name,** or a **scientific name**; more informally it is also historically called a **Latin name**.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] In the zoological code, ICZN, the system is also called **binominal nomenclature** (using the suffix *-inal* instead of *-ial*), meaning "two-name naming system".
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] The first part of the name – the *generic name* – identifies the genus to which the species belongs, whereas the second part – the **specific name** or **specific epithet** – distinguishes the species within the genus.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] For example, modern humans belong to the genus *Homo* and within this genus to the species *Homo sapiens*.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] *Tyrannosaurus rex* is likely the most widely known non-human binomial.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] The *formal* introduction of this system of naming species is credited to Carl Linnaeus, effectively beginning with his work *Species Plantarum* in 1753.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] But as early as 1622, Gaspard Bauhin introduced in his book *Pinax theatri botanici* (English, *Illustrated exposition of plants*) containing many names of genera that were later adopted by Linnaeus.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] The introduction of two-part names (binominal nomenclature) for species by Linnaeus was a welcome simplification because as our knowledge of biodiversity expanded, so did the length of the names, many of which had become unwieldy.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] With all naturalists worldwide adopting binominal nomenclature, there arose several schools of thought about the details.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] It became ever more apparent that a detailed body of rules was necessary to govern scientific names.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] From the mid-19th century onwards, there were several initiatives to arrive at worldwide-accepted sets of rules.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] The starting point, that is the time from which these codes are in effect (usually retroactively), varies from group to group, and sometimes from rank to rank.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] In botany and mycology, the starting point is often 1 May 1753 (Linnaeus, *Species plantarum*).
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] In zoology, it is 1 January 1758 (Linnaeus, *Systema Naturae*, 10th Edition).
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] On the other hand, bacteriology started anew, making a clean sweep in 1980 (Skerman et al., "Approved Lists of Bacterial Names"), although maintaining the original authors and dates of publication.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] There are also differences in the way codes work.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] For example, the *ICN* (the code for algae, fungi and plants) forbids tautonyms, while the *ICZN* (the animal code) allows them.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] These codes differ in terminology, and there is a long-term project to "harmonize" this.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] For instance, the *ICN* uses "valid" in "valid publication of a name" (=the act of publishing a formal name), with "establishing a name" as the *ICZN* equivalent.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] The *ICZN* uses "valid" in "valid name" (="correct name"), with "correct name" as the *ICN* equivalent.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] Harmonization is making very limited progress.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] There are differences in respect of what kinds of types are used.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] The bacteriological code prefers living type cultures, but allows other kinds.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] There has been ongoing debate regarding which kind of type is more useful in a case like cyanobacteria.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] A more radical approach was made in 1997 when the IUBS/IUMS International Committee on Bionomenclature (ICB) presented the long debated *Draft BioCode*, proposed to replace all existing *Codes* with a harmonization of them.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] The originally planned implementation date for the BioCode draft was January 1, 2000, but agreement to replace the existing *Codes* was not reached.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] In 2011, a revised *BioCode* was proposed that, instead of replacing the existing *Codes*, would provide a unified context for them, referring to them when necessary.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] Changes in the existing codes are slowly being made in the proposed directions.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] However, participants of the last serious discussion of the draft BioCode concluded that it would probably not be implemented in their lifetimes.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] Many authors encountered problems in using the Linnean system in phylogenetic classification.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] In fact, early proponents of rank-based nomenclature, such as Alphonse de Candolle and the authors of the 1886 version of the American Ornithologists' Union code of nomenclature already envisioned that in the future, rank-based nomenclature would have to be abandoned.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] Another *Code* that was developed since 1998 is the *PhyloCode*, which now regulates names defined under phylogenetic nomenclature instead of the traditional Linnaean nomenclature.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] This new approach requires using phylogenetic definitions that refer to "specifiers", analogous to "type" under rank-based nomenclature.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] Such definitions delimit taxa under a given phylogeny, and this kind of nomenclature does not require use of absolute ranks.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] The *Code* took effect in 2020, with the publication of Phylonyms, a monograph that includes a list of the first names established under that code.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] Some protists, sometimes called **ambiregnal protists**, have been considered to be both protozoa and algae, or protozoa and fungi, and names for these have been published under either or both of the *ICZN* and the *ICN*.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] The resulting double language throughout protist classification schemes resulted in confusion.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] Slime molds, plasmodial forms and other "fungus-like" organisms claimed by both protozoologists and mycologists include mycetozoans, plasmodiophorids, acrasids, and labyrinthulomycetes.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] Fungi claimed by both protozoologists and mycologists include chytrids, blastoclads, and the gut fungi.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] Other problematic groups are the Cyanobacteria (ICNP/ICN), the Rozellida and Microsporidia (ICZN/ICN).
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] The zoological code does not regulate names of taxa lower than subspecies or higher than superfamily.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] There are many attempts to introduce some order on the nomenclature of these taxa, including the PhyloCode, the Duplostensional Nomenclatural System, and circumscriptional nomenclature.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] The botanical code is applied primarily to the ranks of superfamily and below.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] There are some rules for names above the rank of superfamily, but the principle of priority does not apply to them, and the principle of typification is optional.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] These names may be either automatically typified names or be descriptive names.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] In some circumstances, a taxon has two possible names (e.g., Chrysophyceae Pascher, 1914, *nom. descrip.*; Hibberd, 1976, *nom. typificatum*).
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] Descriptive names are problematic, once that, if a taxon is split, it is not obvious which new group takes the existing name.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] Meanwhile, with typified names, the existing name is taken by the new group that still bears the type of this name.
[src:apicomplexan/biological-nomenclature] However, typified names present special problems for microorganisms.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] In biology, a **common name** is a name of a taxon or organism that is based on the normal language of everyday life.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] It is often contrasted with the scientific name for the same organism, which is often based in Latin.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] Common names can be used frequently, but that is not always the case.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] Creating an "official" list of common names can also be an attempt to standardize the use of common names, which can sometimes vary a great deal between one part of a country and another, as well as between one country and another country, even where the same language is spoken in both places.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] A common name intrinsically plays a part in a classification of objects, typically an incomplete and informal classification, in which some names are degenerate examples in that they are unique and lack reference to any other name, as is the case with say, *ginkgo*, *okapi*, and *ratel*.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] The form of scientific names for organisms, called binomial nomenclature, is superficially similar to the noun-adjective form of vernacular names or common names which were used by non-modern cultures.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] A collective name such as *owl* was made more precise by the addition of an adjective such as *screech*.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] Linnaeus himself published a flora of his homeland Sweden, *Flora Svecica* (1745), and in this, he recorded the Swedish common names, region by region, as well as the scientific names.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] The Swedish common names were all binomials (e.g. plant no.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] 85 Ren-losta); the vernacular binomial system thus preceded his scientific binomial system.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] The geographic range over which a particularly common name is used varies; some common names have a very local application, while others are virtually universal within a particular language.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] Some such names even apply across ranges of languages; the word for *cat*, for instance, is easily recognizable in most Germanic and many Romance languages.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] Many vernacular names, however, are restricted to a single country and colloquial names to local districts.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] Some languages also have more than one common name for the same animal.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] For example, in Irish, there are many terms that are considered outdated but still well-known for their somewhat humorous and poetic descriptions of animals.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] Common names are used in the writings of both professionals and laymen.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] Many examples of such common names simply are attempts to translate the scientific name into English or some other vernacular.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] Such translation may be confusing in itself, or confusingly inaccurate, for example, *gratiosus* does not mean "gracile" and *gracilis* does not mean "graceful".
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] Various bodies and the authors of many technical and semi-technical books do not simply adapt existing common names for various organisms; they try to coin (and put into common use) comprehensive, useful, authoritative, and standardised lists of new names.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] Other attempts to reconcile differences between widely separated regions, traditions, and languages, by arbitrarily imposing nomenclature, often reflect narrow perspectives and have unfortunate outcomes.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] For example, members of the genus *Burhinus* occur in Australia, Southern Africa, Eurasia, and South America.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] A recent trend in field manuals and bird lists is to use the name "thick-knee" for members of the genus.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] This, in spite of the fact that the majority of the species occur in non-English-speaking regions and have various common names, not always English.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] For example, "Dikkop" is the centuries-old South African vernacular name for their two local species: *Burhinus capensis* is the Cape dikkop (or "gewone dikkop", not to mention the presumably much older Zulu name "umBangaqhwa"); *Burhinus vermiculatus* is the "water dikkop".
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] The thick joints in question are not even, in fact, the birds' knees, but the intertarsal joints—in lay terms the ankles.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] Furthermore, not all species in the genus have "thick knees", so the thickness of the "knees" of some species is not of clearly descriptive significance.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] The family Burhinidae has members that have various common names even in English, including "stone curlews", so the choice of the name "thick-knees" is not easy to defend but is a clear illustration of the hazards of the facile coinage of terminology.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] For collective nouns for various subjects, see a list of collective nouns (e.g. a flock of sheep, pack of wolves).
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] Some organizations have created official lists of common names, or guidelines for creating common names, hoping to standardize the use of common names.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] The AFNS has been an official Australian Standard since July 2007 and has existed in draft form (The Australian Fish Names List) since 2001.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] Seafood Services Australia (SSA) serve as the Secretariat for the AFNC.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] The Entomological Society of America maintains a database of official common names of insects, and proposals for new entries must be submitted and reviewed by a formal committee before being added to the listing.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] Efforts to standardize English names for the amphibians and reptiles of North America (north of Mexico) began in the mid-1950s.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] The dynamic nature of taxonomy necessitates periodical updates and changes in the nomenclature of both scientific and common names.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] The Society for the Study of Amphibians and Reptiles (SSAR) published an updated list in 1978, largely following the previous established examples, and subsequently published eight revised editions ending in 2017.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] More recently the SSAR switched to an online version with a searchable database.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] Standardized names for the amphibians and reptiles of Mexico in Spanish and English were first published in 1994, with a revised and updated list published in 2008.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] A set of guidelines for the creation of English names for birds was published in *The Auk* in 1978.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] It gave rise to *Birds of the World: Recommended English Names* and its Spanish and French companions.
[src:apicomplexan/common-name] The Academy of the Hebrew Language publish from time to time short dictionaries of common name in Hebrew for species that occur in Israel or surrounding countries e.g. for Reptilia in 1938, Osteichthyes in 2012, and Odonata in 2015.
